## SLIDE 2 вҖ” LITERATURE SURVEY

**Slide Title:** Literature Survey вҖ” Mapping the Research Landscape

### Column A: AI for Startup Valuation & Investment
- **Sunkara et al. (2025)** вҖ” *"AI-Driven VC Investment"* (WCCEST 2025): Established that ensemble ML models (XGBoost, LightGBM) outperform single-model approaches in startup success prediction. Identified trust signals and GitHub activity as key predictors. Limitation: No finance-layer integration or blockchain governance.
- **Li et al. (2025)** вҖ” *"HedgeAgents"* (WWW 2025): Multi-agent LLM trading system covering profitability, risk control, explainability, and diversity; outperforms all baselines on PRUDEX benchmark. Does not address early-stage startup valuation.
- **Yan et al. (2025)** вҖ” *"TradeTrap"* (2025): Shows LLM-based trading agents are vulnerable to adversarial perturbations, inducing portfolio drawdowns. Argues for deterministic rule-based guards вҖ” aligned with IntelliStake's trust-threshold oracle freeze.
- **Zhang et al. (2025)** вҖ” *"Are LLM-based Agents Truly Reliable?"*: Systematic evaluation showing LLM agents have 20%-40% failure rates in financial tasks without deterministic fallback layers.

### Column B: Portfolio Optimization
- **Sun et al. (2025)** вҖ” *"LLM-Enhanced Black-Litterman Portfolio Optimization"*: Integrates LLM-generated investor views directly into the BL posterior; achieves annualized Sharpe of 1.2вҖ“1.8 on Chinese equity markets. Our system uses R.A.I.S.E. trust scores as views instead of LLM-generated text.
- **Kim et al. (2023) вҖ” Springer Nature (Asia Pacific Financial Markets)**: Demonstrates that incorporating alternative data (news sentiment, ESG signals) into mean-variance optimization improves Sharpe ratios by 15вҖ“22% over traditional MVO. Supports IntelliStake's sentiment-weighted BL approach.
- **SSRN (2022) вҖ” Quantitative Portfolio Theory**: Formal proof that Black-Litterman posterior outperforms equal-weight and min-variance benchmarks when investor views are accurate. Sets theoretical baseline for our approach.

### Column C: Blockchain, DeFi & Oracle Security
- **Deng et al. (2024)** вҖ” *"Safeguarding DeFi Smart Contracts against Oracle Deviations"*: OVer framework uses symbolic analysis + SMT solvers to detect oracle manipulation. Shows that 10/10 DeFi benchmarks are vulnerable to skewed oracle inputs. IntelliStake addresses this via multi-source aggregation and cryptographic signing.
- **Kreppmeier et al. (2023) вҖ” Journal of Banking & Finance**: Analysis of 173 real-estate security token offerings (STOs) and 238,433 blockchain transactions. Shows STOs lower barriers to investment but crypto sentiment dominates fundamentals вҖ” motivating AI-governed oracle in IntelliStake.
- **Piper et al. (2024)** вҖ” *"KYC-Compliant dApps"*: Proposes SSI + ZKP for DeFi permissioning; shows performance improvement over baseline KYC. IntelliStake implements ERC-3643 (T-REX) for permissioned wallets вҖ” a production-standard equivalent.
- **Rashid & Hayat (2024) вҖ” AMLGaurd**: Graph Auto-Encoder for AML detection in financial networks, classifying 4 anomaly types. IntelliStake uses Isolation Forest for hype/fraud detection; related but lighter-weight for startup context.

### Column D: Explainability & Risk
- **EU AI Act XAI Paper (2024)**: Maps SHAP/LIME explainability to EU AI Act obligations for high-risk AI in finance. Establishes that explainable AI is legally required for automated investment decisions. IntelliStake implements SHAP (TreeSHAP) for trust score breakdowns.
- **Multi-Agent Systems (2025)**: Reviews multi-agent orchestration for financial decisions вҖ” IntelliStake's Investment Committee (Quant + Auditor + Newsroom + Manager) is a direct implementation of this paradigm.

**Speaker Notes:** This slide maps the 4 pillars of our literature review: ML for valuation, portfolio math, blockchain governance, and XAI. The key gap across all papers is the absence of an end-to-end integrated platform.

